# PDL (Peripheral Driver Layer) Configuration

menuconfig PDL
	bool "PDL (Peripheral Driver Layer)"
	default n
	depends on OSAL && HAL && PCONFIG
	help
	  Peripheral Driver Layer provides high-level peripheral management
	  and protocol handling.

	  PDL sits above HAL and provides:
	  - Protocol-aware peripheral drivers
	  - Device abstraction (MCU modules, PMC)
	  - State management and error handling
	  - Unified API for complex peripherals

	  Architecture:
	  PDL uses HAL for low-level hardware access and PCONFIG for
	  hardware configuration, providing application-level APIs
	  for managing complex peripheral subsystems.

	  Memory footprint: ~15KB base + per-peripheral drivers

	  Supported peripherals:
	  - MCU modules (microcontroller peripherals)
	  - PMC (Communication Control Module)

	  Dependencies: OSAL, HAL, PCONFIG

	  Note: Enable OSAL, HAL, PCONFIG, and TYPES first in "Core Modules" menu.

	  Recommended: Enable for systems with complex peripheral management

	  If unsure, say Y.

if PDL

menu "PDL Build Configuration"

config PDL_BUILD_STATIC
	bool "Build static library (.a)"
	default y
	help
	  Build PDL as a static library (libpdl.a).

	  Static linking advantages:
	  - No runtime dependencies
	  - Peripheral drivers embedded in executable
	  - Slightly faster

	  Recommended: Enable for embedded systems

config PDL_BUILD_SHARED
	bool "Build shared library (.so)"
	default n
	help
	  Build PDL as a shared library (libpdl.so).

	  Shared library advantages:
	  - Can update peripheral drivers without recompiling apps
	  - Smaller executable size
	  - Code sharing between processes

	  Recommended: Enable for multi-application systems

endmenu

menuconfig PDL_MCU_SUPPORT
	bool "MCU peripheral support"
	default n
	help
	  Enable MCU (Microcontroller) peripheral support.

	  MCU peripherals are microcontroller-based modules that provide
	  specialized control and monitoring functions, offloading tasks
	  from the main processor.

	  Typical MCU functions:
	  - Real-time sensor data acquisition
	  - PWM control for motors/actuators
	  - Analog signal processing
	  - Low-level protocol handling

	  Communication options:
	  - CAN bus (for robust, multi-drop networks)
	  - UART (for point-to-point connections)

	  Memory footprint: ~8KB base + protocol overhead

	  You can enable CAN-based or UART-based MCU support in the submenu.

	  If unsure, say Y.

source "core/pdl/src/pdl_mcu/Config.in"

menuconfig PDL_PMC_SUPPORT
	bool "PMC (Communication Control Module) support"
	default n
	select OSAL_NETWORK
	help
	  Enable PMC (Communication Control Module) for PMC communication.

	  PMC provides high-level interface with PMC (Power Management
	  Controller) over Ethernet, handling:
	  - TCP/IP socket communication
	  - Message framing and CRC validation
	  - Connection management and auto-reconnect
	  - Command/response protocol

	  Features:
	  - Reliable TCP-based communication
	  - Automatic message sequencing
	  - Configurable timeouts
	  - Thread-safe operation

	  Memory footprint: ~8KB

	  Communication protocol:
	  - Frame: [Magic][Type][Rsv][SeqNum][Len][CRC32][Payload]
	  - Magic number: 0xAA55
	  - CRC32 validation for data integrity

	  Use cases:
	  - PMC power management and monitoring
	  - Remote system control
	  - Distributed power systems

	  Dependencies: OSAL_NETWORK (for socket API)

	  If unsure, say N.

source "core/pdl/src/pdl_pmc/Config.in"

endif # PDL
